For Xamarin-based projects, you should use the `sqlite-net-pcl` NuGet package, which is a lightweight and fast SQLite library that works on multiple platforms, including iOS, Android, and UWP. The package also provides a simple and easy-to-use ORM.

To use `sqlite-net-pcl`, you'll need to make a few adjustments to your existing code. First, install the NuGet package:

```
Install-Package sqlite-net-pcl
```

Next, adjust your code to use the SQLite types provided by `sqlite-net-pcl`. Here's an example of how you could modify your `SqLiteDatabase` class:

```csharp
using SQLite;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class SqLiteDatabase
{
    private readonly SQLiteAsyncConnection _connection;

    public SqLiteDatabase(string databaseName)
    {
        _connection = new SQLiteAsyncConnection(databaseName + ".db");
        InitializeDatabase();
    }
    private async void InitializeDatabase()
    {
        await _connection.CreateTableAsync<User>();
        await _connection.CreateTableAsync<Card>();
        await _connection.CreateTableAsync<UserCard>();
    }
}
```

Now you'll need to adjust your `User`, `Card`, and `UserCard` classes to use the appropriate attributes provided by `sqlite-net-pcl`. Here's an example:

```csharp
public class User
{
    [PrimaryKey]
    public string Id { get; set; }
    // other properties and methods
}

public class Card
{
    [PrimaryKey]
    public string Id { get; set; }

    // other properties and methods
}

public class UserCard
{
    [PrimaryKey, AutoIncrement]
    public int Id { get; set; }
    [ForeignKey(typeof(User))]
    public string UserId { get; set; }
    [ForeignKey(typeof(Card))]
    public string CardId { get; set; }
    public long Timestamp { get; set; }
}
```

Lastly, replace your existing data access methods with their equivalent `sqlite-net-pcl` async methods. For example, instead of the `GetOrAddUserAsync` method, you can use:

```csharp
public async Task<User> GetOrAddUserAsync(string userId)
{
    var user = await _connection.FindAsync<User>(userId);
    if (user != null) return user;

    user = new User { Id = userId };
    await _connection.InsertAsync(user);
    return user;
}
```

By making these changes, your code should work well with Xamarin and you'll be able to create an Android app using your existing C# skills.

Apologies for the confusion earlier. sqlite-net-pcl does not support composite primary keys by using the PrimaryKey attribute. However, you can define the composite primary key by inheriting from `TableMapping` and overriding the `FindColumnWithPrimaryKey` method. 

Here's an example of how you could create a `UserCard` class with a composite primary key:

```csharp
using SQLite;

public class UserCard
{
    public string UserId { get; set; }
    public string CardId { get; set; }
    public long Timestamp { get; set; }

    public class UserCardTableMapping : TableMapping
    {
        public UserCardTableMapping() : base(typeof(UserCard))
        {
            UseCompositePrimaryKey = true;
        }

        protected override Column FindColumnWithPrimaryKey()
        {
            return GetColumn("UserId");
        }
    }
}
```

Now, when initializing your `SqLiteDatabase`, instead of using the `CreateTableAsync<UserCard>()` method, you'll register the custom `UserCardTableMapping` type:

```csharp
private async void InitializeDatabase()
{
    await _connection.CreateTableAsync<User>();
